ught, bringing together global justice, human rights, and corporate responsibility. Conceiving of corporate social responsibility (CSR) from this unique perspective, author Florian Wettstein takes readers well beyond the limitations of conventional notions, which tend to focus on either beneficence or pure charity. While the call for multinationals' involvement in the solution of global problems has become stronger in recent times, few specifics have been laid down regarding how to hold those institutions accountable in the global arena. This text attempts to work out the normative basis underlying the responsibilities of multinational corporations-thereby filling a crucial void in the literature and marking a milestone in the CSR debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHuman rights. 0aInternational business enterprisesxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Government & Business.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804772600zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804772600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804772600.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles